<body>
<h2>component</h2>
    <p>This keyword is used to define component. For example: </p>
    <pre class="code">
[
    uuid(9b9d422d-b9cc-4658-9f94-3dff2667e89b),
    uunm(http://www.koretide.com/car/ComponentDemo.dll)
]
<b>component</b> ComponentDemo
{
    [uuid(6bd80415-d91b-44f2-9e44-b3e11ed50d65)]
    interface IInterface {
        ECODE Func([in] int num);
    }
    [uuid(8bc5829e-ad6e-4b2f-91c5-8c17f38e9110)]
    class CClass {
        interface IInterface;
    }
}
</pre>
    <p>In the sample, a component ComponentDemo was defined. This component defines a interface IInterface and a class CClass.</p>
    <p>In the "[]" before the component keyword is the attribute of this component. Component attributes modify component.The <a class="style1" href="../attributes/attributes_uuid.htm">uuid</a> and <a class="style1" href="../attributes/attributes_uunm.htm">uunm</a> attribute are essential. This uuid in component attribute is called component ID and it uniquely identifies a component. uunm specifies the Internet location of the dll file that the component is in. Other attributes can be included in component attribute. Please see <a class="style1" href="../attribute.htm">CAR Attribute</a> for details.</p>
    <p>After the component keyword comes the name of the component. <b>Remarks: </b>When defining component name, in order to avoid confusion, it is better to use component name similar to this CAR file name.</p>
    <p>Inside the "{}" of component keyword is the definition of this component. Component definition includes interface definition to be implemented, class definition and type definition.</p>
    <ul><font color="red"><b>Note: </b>In a CAR file there can be one and only one component keyword.Thus there can be only one component in a CAR file.</font></ul>
